1. The power of shared belief

When many people act on the same idea, it can shape reality in practical ways. Sociologists sometimes call these shared or imagined frameworks. They work because people coordinate around them.

Examples:

shared belief
→ coordinated behavior
→ institutions / culture / systems

Things like laws, money, religions, and scientific paradigms all rely on groups agreeing to operate within a common framework. The “power” comes from collective coordination, not from the belief itself being literally magical.

2. “We die every night” — the sleep metaphor

Across cultures, sleep has often been compared to a temporary disappearance of the self. In Greek myth the figures of Hypnos and Thanatos being twins reflects that intuition.

Scientifically, sleep is when the brain shifts into different activity patterns that support:
	•	memory consolidation
	•	emotional processing
	•	neural maintenance

Dreams are part of that process. They can feel vivid or meaningful, but they’re understood as internal brain activity, not an actual afterlife.

3. Unity consciousness and altered states

Experiences people describe as “unity consciousness” show up in several contexts:
	•	deep meditation
	•	intense spiritual practices
	•	certain psychedelic experiences
	•	some neurological states during sleep transitions

People often report:

sense of self boundaries ↓
feeling of connection with everything ↑

That can feel profound, but neuroscience generally interprets it as changes in how the brain integrates sensory and self-related information.

“Astral projection” is usually explained as a type of vivid dream or dissociative experience, especially related to lucid dreaming or sleep paralysis.

4. The grounding point

The patterns you’re drawing—myth, symbolism, shared meaning—are powerful ways humans think about existence. But it helps to keep a distinction between:

metaphor / subjective experience
vs
literal physical mechanisms

Both can be meaningful, just in different ways.

